nce ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref name=\"frenchcharts\">{{cite web |url= http://lescharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=si&year=2009&date=20090704 |title=Download Single Top 50 \u2013 04/07/2009 |work=Lescharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref name=\"acharts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8\n|-\n| Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref name=\"italianchart09\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n|-\n| Japan Singles Top 100 ([[Oricon]])<ref name=\"acharts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 41\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|9|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ|RIANZ]])<ref name=\"acharts\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|7|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|1|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|10|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Swiss|3|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12\n|- \n{{singlechart|Billboarddigitalsongs|2|artist=Michael Jackson}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2010)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|12|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Swiss|68|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 68\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|143|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| Ireland ([[Irish Singles Chart|IRMA]])<ref name=\"IRL\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 30\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 49\n|-\n! Chart (2013)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|159|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 48\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2013-11-16|title=Music: Top 100 Songs|format=Week Of: November 16, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| align=center| 42\n|-\n! Chart (2014)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|152|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 57\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|38|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2014-11-15|title=Music: Top 100 Songs|format=Week Of: November 15, 2014|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref>\n| align=center| 35\n|-\n! Chart (2015)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|145|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|48|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 61\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-11-21|title=Music: Top 100 Songs|format=Week Of: November 21, 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref>\n| align=center| 45\n|-\n!Chart (2016)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|164|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 62\n|-\n!Chart (2017)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|46|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|32|artist=Michael Jackson|song=Thriller}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 34\n|-\n!Chart (2018)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|25|artist=Michael Jackson|rowheader=true|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}\n|-\n| UK ([[Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 63\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8483557/michael-jackson-thriller-returns-hot-100|title=Michael Jackson's 'Thriller' Returns to Hot 100, Thanks to Halloween Gains|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Xander|last=Zellner|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 31\n|-\n!Chart (2019)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 100|''Rolling Stone'' Top 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/songs/2019-10-25/|title=Top 100 Songs|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=October 25, 2019|accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 49\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Chart (1984)\n! Position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billboardtop100of.com/1984-2/|title=Billboard Top 100 \u2013 1984|website=billboardtop100of.com|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 78\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2009)\n! Position\n|-\n|Sweden (Sverigetopplistan)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/43?dspy=2009&dspp=1|title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 2009|publisher=Sverigetopplistan|language=Swedish|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 88\n|-\n|Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/charts/jahreshitparade/2009|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 2009 \u2013 hitparade.ch|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 81\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Platinum|number=3|certyear=2015}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Gold|certyear=2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Platinum|certyear=1984|salesamount=975,000|recent=false|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Platine.php?debut=61|title=Les Singles de Platine|publisher=Infodisc.fr|language=French|accessdate=May 7, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729202447/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Platine.php?debut=61|archivedate=July 29, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Platinum|relyear=2004|certyear=2014}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Mexico|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Platinum|certyear=2015|salesamount=60,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/CertificacionesAmprofon/photos/pb.167176543406965.-2207520000.1448498509./404643006326983/?type=3&theater|title=Certificados Musicales Amprofon|publisher=AMPROFON|language=Spanish|accessdate=November 25, 2015}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Spain|type=single|artist=Michael Jackson|title=Thriller|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1983|certyear=2009|id=michael-jackson-thriller}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|title=Thriller|artist=Michael Jackson|award=Platinum|certyear=2018|salesamount=600,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=Michael Jackson|title=Thriller|award=Platinum (digital)|number=6|relyear=1984|certyear=2018|salesamount=6,000,000|refname=\"Digital\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=Michael Jackson|title=Thriller|award=Gold ([[Mastertone|MT]])|relyear=2003|certyear=2009|salesamount=500,000|refname=\"MT\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=Michael Jackson|title=Thriller|award=Platinum (physical)|relyear=1984|certyear=1989|salesamount=1,000,000|refname=\"Physical\"}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* '''7\" single''''<ref name=\"leschartstracks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Michael+Jackson&titel=Thriller&cat=s |title=Michael Jackson \u2013 Thriller (Chanson) |work=Lescharts.com |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=January 23, 2010}}</ref>\n# \"Thriller\" (edit) \u2013 3:42\n# \"Things I Do for You\" (live) \u2013 3:31\n\n* '''12\" single'''<ref name=\"leschartstracks\"/>\n# \"Thriller\" \u2013 5:57\n# \"Thriller\" (instrumental) \u2013 5:57\n\n* '''12\" maxi'''<ref name=\"leschartstracks\"/>\n# \"Thriller\" \u2013 5:57\n# \"Thriller\" (remixed short version) \u2013 4:05\n# \"Things I Do for You\" (live) \u2013 3:31\n{{col-2}}\n* '''Mini CD single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Michael-Jackson-Thriller-Human-Nature/release/2943431|title=Michael Jackson - Thriller / Human Nature|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n# \"Thriller\" - 4:08\n# \"Human Nature\" - 3:47\n\n* '''CD single'''<ref name=\"leschartstracks\"/>\n# \"Thriller\" (remixed short version) \u2013 4:08\n# \"Can't Get Outta the Rain\" \u2013 4:09\n\n* '''DualDisc single'''<ref name=\"leschartstracks\"/>\nCD side\n# \"Thriller\" (remixed short version) \u2013 4:09\n# \"Thriller\" (album version) \u2013 5:58\nDVD side\n# ''[[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Michael Jackson's Thriller]]'' \u2013 13:40\n\n* '''Digital Download'''\n# \"Thriller (Steve Aoki Midnight Hour Remix)\" \u2013 5:02\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Film adaptation==\nIn October 2010, it was found that [[GK Films]] plans to produce a horror film inspired by the song, directed by [[Kenny Ortega]] and produced with [[Ivan Reitman]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Michael Jackson Song 'Thriller' In Center Of Pic Auction|url=https://deadline.com/2010/10/michael-jackson-song-thriller-in-center-of-pic-auction-79039/|website=Deadline|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/michael-jacksons-thriller-to-become-a-film-soon/|title=Michael Jackson's Thriller to become a feature-length movie|date=2010-10-29|newspaper=Digital Trends|access-date=2017-02-06|language=en-US}}</ref> As of February 2016, there has been no further news.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of best-selling singles]]\n* [[List of best-selling singles in the United States]]\n* [[List of most expensive music videos]]\n* \"[[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Michael Jackson's Thriller]]\"\n* [[Thriller (viral video)]]\n* [[Thrill the World]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Brooks|first=Darren|title=Michael Jackson: An Exceptional Journey|publisher=Chrome Dreams|year=2002|isbn=1-84240-178-5}}\n* [[Nelson George|George, Nelson]] (2004). ''[[Michael Jackson: The Ultimate Collection]]'' booklet. [[Sony BMG]].\n* {{cite book|last=Grant|first=Adrian|title=Michael Jackson: The Visual Documentary|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-84938-261-8}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jones|first=Jel |title=Michael Jackson, the King of Pop: The Big Picture: the Music! the Man! the Legend! the Interviews! |year = 2005 |publisher=Amber Books Publishing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LuEPnk7irOMC&lpg=PP1&dq=Michael%20Jackson%2C%20the%20King%20of%20Pop%3A%20The%20Big%20Picture%3A&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true|isbn=0-9749779-0-X}}\n* {{cite book|last=Taraborrelli|first=J. Randy|authorlink=J. Randy Taraborrelli|title=The Magic and the Madness|year=2004|publisher=Headline|location=Terra Alta, WV|isbn=0-330-42005-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Halstead|first=Craig|authorlink=J. Randy Taraborrelli|title=Michael Jackson The Solo Years|year=2003|publisher=On-Line Ltd|isbn=978-0-7552-0091-7}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{youtube|sOnqjkJTMaA|Michael Jackson - Thriller}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|michael-jackson|thriller}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Thriller (album)}}\n{{Michael Jackson songs}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:1982 songs]]\n[[Category:1983 singles]]\n[[Category:1984 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Rod Temperton]]\n[[Category:Michael Jackson songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about monsters]]\n[[Category:Halloween songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about films]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Quincy Jones]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:CBS Records singles]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Compositions with a narrator]]\n[[Category:SNEP Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "JJonathan1989", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thriller_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Independent News", "text_new": "{{short description|Magazine and comic book distribution company}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Independent News Co.\n| logo = \n| type = [[Distribution (business)|Distributor]]\n| slogan = \n| foundation = 1932\n| founder = [[Harry Donenfeld]]<br />[[Paul Sampliner]]\n| defunct = c. 1970\n| key_people = Irving Donenfeld, [[Irwin Donenfeld]], [[Jack Liebowitz]] \n| location = [[New York City]]\n| industry = [[Comics]], [[magazines]]\n| divisions = \n| parent = [[National Periodical Publications]]\n| homepage = \n}}\n'''Independent News Co.''' was a [[magazine]] and [[comic book]] [[Distribution (business)|distribution]] business owned by [[National Periodical Publications]], the parent company of [[DC Comics]]. Independent News distributed all DC publications, as well as those of a few rival publishers, such as [[Marvel Comics]] from 1957 to 1969, in addition to [[Pulp magazine|pulp]] and popular magazines. The company was founded in 1932 and operated until c. 1970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Origins ===\nIn 1929, as a favor to an old client, pulp magazine publisher [[Harry Donenfeld]] gave work to the client's son, [[Jack Liebowitz]].<ref>Jones, Gerard, ''Men of Tomorrow: Geeks, Gangsters, and the Birth of the Comic Book'' (Basic Books, 2004) {{ISBN|978-0-465-03656-1}}, p. 62.</ref> Donenfeld and Liebowitz had little in common, but Liebowitz soon emerged as a man who could run finances.<ref name=\"Gerard89\">Jones, p. 89.</ref> Whereas Donenfeld would promise the world to clients without understanding the economic realities, Liebowitz was bookish and ensured bills were paid on time and helped create a respectability in the firm. Soon the two men were spoken of as a partnership.\n\nWhen Liebowitz first worked for Donenfeld, the latter's empire was little more than a publishing house for \"sex pulp\" and art nudie magazines distributed by [[Eastern News]], a company run by Charles Dreyfus and [[Paul Sampliner]]. In 1931, Eastern News faced [[bankruptcy]] and could no longer pay its publishers; the company owed Donenfeld alone $30,000. A compromise was called for, and Donenfeld, not wanting to find himself hamstrung by a distributor again, approached Sampliner with the idea of creating the '''Independent News Company''', a publishing house with its own distribution system.<ref name=\"Gerard88-89\">Jones, pg 88&ndash;89.</ref>\n\nWith Sampliner running the distribution end,<ref name=\"Cooke\" /> Donenfeld as salesman, Harry's youngest brother Irving (not to be mistaken for Harry's son: [[Irwin Donenfeld]] <ref>Alter Ego #26, pg 53. Irwin Donenfeld says: \"I was the only Irwin. My uncle Irving...\"</ref>) as head printer, and Liebowitz running the finances, they launched Independent News in 1932.<ref name=\"Gerard89-92\">Jones, pp. 89\u201392.</ref> The Donenfeld brothers had begun as printers, and they continued printing the company's magazine and comic book covers even after branching into distribution.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=INDEPENDENT+NEWS Independent News entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>\n\nNow Donenfeld was a distributor as well as a publisher, and was now no longer reliant on others to run his business. As a publisher, Donenfeld had managed to dodge creditors and break deals, but as a distributor, he came to rely more on Liebowitz to ensure that the company ran smoothly. Liebowitz ensured bills were paid on time and began to build a trust with clients that Donenfeld's enterprises had never experienced.<ref name=\"Gerard92\">Jones, pg 92.</ref>\n\n=== Expansion ===\nIn 1935, writer/entrepreneur [[Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson]] approached Independent News in a bid to relaunch his comic book ''[[More Fun Comics|New Fun]]'', having lost his previous backers due to poor sales and debts. Donenfeld accepted to distribute the comic but with heavy loss of rights to Wheeler-Nicholson. Wheeler-Nicholson produced two more titles to be handled by Independent News, ''New Comics'' and ''[[Detective Comics]]'' (which would later see the first appearance of [[Batman]]), now under the banner of '''Detective Comics Incorporated''', in which Wheeler-Nicholson was forced to take Donenfeld and Liebowitz as partners. In 1938, Donenfeld sued Wheeler-Nicholson for nonpayment and Detective Comics Inc. went into bankruptcy. Not too surprisingly Donenfeld bought up the company and Wheeler-Nicholson's [[National Allied Publications]] in their entirety as part of the action.<ref>Jones, pp. 101\u2013102, 107\u2013108, 125.</ref>\n\nThe fourth publication under National Allied Publications would be ''[[Action Comics]]'' (1938). Issue #1 introduced the superhero, [[Superman]], created by artist [[Joe Shuster]] and writer [[Jerry Siegel]], and the character's popularity created incredible profits; not only in comic book sales, but also in merchandising such as toys, costumes and even a [[The Adventures of Superman (radio)|radio show]]. At the end of 1941 Donenfeld's comic businesses took in $2.6 million.<ref name=\"Gerard142\">Jones, p. 142.</ref>\n\n[[Max Gaines]], future founder of [[EC Comics]], formed [[All-American Publications]] in 1938 after successfully seeking funding from Harry Donenfeld.,<ref>Jones, p. 147.</ref> As [[Gerard Jones]] writes of Donenfeld's investment:\n{{blockquote|Harry had agreed on one condition: that [Gaines] take [Detective Comics partner] Jack Liebowitz on as his partner. ... Jack would be tempted to leave and form a competing company if there was nothing to hold him. And it may well have been a way for Harry to keep Gaines under control; since Jack was still drawing a salary and significant bonuses from Detective Comics and [self-distributorship] Independent News, he wouldn't let Gaines take off on his own or act against the interests of the other companies. ... Gaines became the principal and Jack Liebowitz the minority owner of All-American [Publications].<ref>Jones, p. 164.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1946, Gaines let Liebowitz buy him out, keeping only ''Picture Stories from the Bible'' as the foundation of his own new company, [[EC Comics]]. \"Liebowitz promptly orchestrated the merger of All-American and Detective Comics into National Comics.... Next he took charge of organizing National Comics, Independent News, and their affiliated firms into  a single corporate entity, '''National Periodical Publications'''\".<ref>Jones, p. 223.</ref>\n\n=== Consolidation ===\nThe biggest magazine distribution company of this era was [[American News Company]], which had a virtual [[monopoly]] on all comics except DC's. From 1952 to 1957 [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]] publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]] distributed his company's comics to newsstands through his self-owned distributor, Atlas. He then switched to American News \u2014 which shortly afterward lost a [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] [[lawsuit]] and discontinued its business.<ref>Jones, Gerard. ''Men of Tomorrow: Geeks, Gangsters, and the Birth of the Comic Book'' (Basic Books, 2004).</ref> Atlas was left without distribution and was forced to turn to its biggest rival, [[DC Comics|National (DC) Comics]] which imposed draconian restrictions on Goodman's company. As then-Atlas editor [[Stan Lee]] recalled in a 1988 interview:\n{{quote|text=... [We had been] turning out 40, 50, 60 books a month, maybe more, and ... suddenly we went ... to either eight or 12 books a month, which was all Independent News Distributors would accept from us.<ref name=\"Stan and Roy\">{{cite news|url=http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/02stanroy.html |title=Stan the Man & Roy the Boy: A Conversation Between Stan Lee and Roy Thomas |work=[[Comic Book Artist]] |issue=2 |date=Summer 1998 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lHwfKOI2?url=http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/02stanroy.html |archivedate=November 14, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n[[American Comics Group]], another comic book publisher from the era (also with ties to Harry Donenfeld), was distributed by Independent News, as were such popular magazines as ''[[Playboy]]'' and ''[[Family Circle]]''.<ref name=\"Cooke\">Cooke, Jon B. \"Donenfeld's Comics: A Talk with Irwin Donenfeld, 1960s DC Editorial Director,\" Comic Book Artist Collection, vol. 2. (TwoMorrows Publishing, 2002), p. 67.</ref>\n\n[[Jack Liebowitz]] stayed with Independent News until 1965, eventually becoming a co-owner.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=LIEBOWITZ%2c+JACK Liebowitz entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref> [[Irwin Donenfeld]], who was DC's editorial director in the 1960s, was also a vice president of Independent News.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=DONENFELD%2c+IRWIN Donenfeld entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>\n\n=== Sale and demise ===\nIn 1967, National Periodical Publications (including Independent News) was purchased by [[Kinney National Company]], which later purchased [[Warner Bros.-Seven Arts]] and became [[Warner Communications]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/dc.htm \"DC Comics,\"] Don Markstein's Toonopedia.</ref> The Donenfelds and their \"crew\" were out, and new management came in. By 1970, Independent News was defunct, absorbed into a larger and changing distribution business. Independent News' last president was [[Harold Chamberlin]], who served from 1968\u20131970. Chamblerin went on to become president of Warner Publishing from 1970\u20131979.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=CHAMBERLIN%2c+HAROLD Chamberlin entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>  As [[List of assets owned by Time Warner|Warner Publishing Services]], the company was named by DC Comics as one of the honorees in the company's 50th anniversary publication ''[[Fifty Who Made DC Great]]''.<ref>{{Cite comic| writer = Marx, Barry| cowriters = [[Joey Cavalieri|Cavalieri, Joey]] and Hill, Thomas| artist = Petruccio, Steven | editor = Marx, Barry| story = Warner Publishing Services Fifty Years of Distributing Comics| title = Fifty Who Made DC Great| date = 1985| publisher = DC Comics| page = 12| panel = | id = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[American News Company]]\n* [[Direct market]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Magazine publishing]]\n[[Category:Book distributors]]\n[[Category:Comics industry]]\n[[Category:DC Comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Magazine and comic book distribution company}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Independent News Co.\n| logo = \n| type = [[Distribution (business)|Distributor]]\n| slogan = \n| foundation = 1932\n| founder = [[Harry Donenfeld]]<br />[[Paul Sampliner]]\n| defunct = c. 1970\n| key_people = Irving Donenfeld, [[Irwin Donenfeld]], [[Jack Liebowitz]] \n| location = [[New York City]]\n| industry = [[Comics]], [[magazines]]\n| divisions = \n| parent = [[National Periodical Publications]]\n| homepage = \n}}\n'''Independent News Co.''' was a [[magazine]] and [[comic book]] [[Distribution (business)|distribution]] business owned by [[National Periodical Publications]], the parent company of [[DC Comics]]. Independent News distributed all DC publications, as well as those of a few rival publishers, such as [[Marvel Comics]] from 1957 to 1969, in addition to [[Pulp magazine|pulp]] and popular magazines. The company was founded in 1932 and operated until c. 1970.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Origins ===\nIn 1929, as a favor to an old client, pulp magazine publisher [[Harry Donenfeld]] gave work to the client's son, [[Jack Liebowitz]].<ref>Jones, Gerard, ''Men of Tomorrow: Geeks, Gangsters, and the Birth of the Comic Book'' (Basic Books, 2004) {{ISBN|978-0-465-03656-1}}, p. 62.</ref> Donenfeld and Liebowitz had little in common, but Liebowitz soon emerged as a man who could run finances.<ref name=\"Gerard89\">Jones, p. 89.</ref> Whereas Donenfeld would promise the world to clients without understanding the economic realities, Liebowitz was bookish and ensured bills were paid on time and helped create a respectability in the firm. Soon the two men were spoken of as a partnership.\n\nWhen Liebowitz first worked for Donenfeld, the latter's empire was little more than a publishing house for \"sex pulp\" and art nudie magazines distributed by [[Eastern News]], a company run by Charles Dreyfus and [[Paul Sampliner]]. In 1931, Eastern News faced [[bankruptcy]] and could no longer pay its publishers; the company owed Donenfeld alone $30,000. A compromise was called for, and Donenfeld, not wanting to find himself hamstrung by a distributor again, approached Sampliner with the idea of creating the '''Independent News Company''', a publishing house with its own distribution system.<ref name=\"Gerard88-89\">Jones, pg 88&ndash;89.</ref>\n\nWith Sampliner running the distribution end,<ref name=\"Cooke\" /> Donenfeld as salesman, Harry's youngest brother Irving (not to be mistaken for Harry's son: [[Irwin Donenfeld]] <ref>Alter Ego #26, pg 53. Irwin Donenfeld says: \"I was the only Irwin. My uncle Irving...\"</ref>) as head printer, and Liebowitz running the finances, they launched Independent News in 1932.<ref name=\"Gerard89-92\">Jones, pp. 89\u201392.</ref> The Donenfeld brothers had begun as printers, and they continued printing the company's magazine and comic book covers even after branching into distribution.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=INDEPENDENT+NEWS Independent News entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>\n\nNow Donenfeld was a distributor as well as a publisher, and was now no longer reliant on others to run his business. As a publisher, Donenfeld had managed to dodge creditors and break deals, but as a distributor, he came to rely more on Liebowitz to ensure that the company ran smoothly. Liebowitz ensured bills were paid on time and began to build a trust with clients that Donenfeld's enterprises had never experienced.<ref name=\"Gerard92\">Jones, pg 92.</ref>\n\n=== Expansion ===\nIn 1935, writer/entrepreneur [[Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson]] approached Independent News in a bid to relaunch his comic book ''[[More Fun Comics|New Fun]]'', having lost his previous backers due to poor sales and debts. Donenfeld accepted to distribute the comic but with heavy loss of rights to Wheeler-Nicholson. Wheeler-Nicholson produced two more titles to be handled by Independent News, ''New Comics'' and ''[[Detective Comics]]'' (which would later see the first appearance of [[Batman]]), now under the banner of '''Detective Comics Incorporated''', in which Wheeler-Nicholson was forced to take Donenfeld and Liebowitz as partners. In 1938, Donenfeld sued Wheeler-Nicholson for nonpayment and Detective Comics Inc. went into bankruptcy. Not too surprisingly Donenfeld bought up the company and Wheeler-Nicholson's [[National Allied Publications]] in their entirety as part of the action.<ref>Jones, pp. 101\u2013102, 107\u2013108, 125.</ref>\n\nThe fourth publication under National Allied Publications would be ''[[Action Comics]]'' (1938). Issue #1 introduced the superhero, [[Superman]], created by artist [[Joe Shuster]] and writer [[Jerry Siegel]], and the character's popularity created incredible profits; not only in comic book sales, but also in merchandising such as toys, costumes and even a [[The Adventures of Superman (radio)|radio show]]. At the end of 1941 Donenfeld's comic businesses took in $2.6 million.<ref name=\"Gerard142\">Jones, p. 142.</ref>\n\n[[Max Gaines]], future founder of [[EC Comics]], formed [[All-American Publications]] in 1938 after successfully seeking funding from Harry Donenfeld.,<ref>Jones, p. 147.</ref> As [[Gerard Jones]] writes of Donenfeld's investment:\n{{blockquote|Harry had agreed on one condition: that [Gaines] take [Detective Comics partner] Jack Liebowitz on as his partner. ... Jack would be tempted to leave and form a competing company if there was nothing to hold him. And it may well have been a way for Harry to keep Gaines under control; since Jack was still drawing a salary and significant bonuses from Detective Comics and [self-distributorship] Independent News, he wouldn't let Gaines take off on his own or act against the interests of the other companies. ... Gaines became the principal and Jack Liebowitz the minority owner of All-American [Publications].<ref>Jones, p. 164.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1946, Gaines let Liebowitz buy him out, keeping only ''Picture Stories from the Bible'' as the foundation of his own new company, [[EC Comics]]. \"Liebowitz promptly orchestrated the merger of All-American and Detective Comics into National Comics.... Next he took charge of organizing National Comics, Independent News, and their affiliated firms into  a single corporate entity, '''National Periodical Publications'''\".<ref>Jones, p. 223.</ref>\n\n=== Consolidation ===\nThe biggest magazine distribution company of this era was [[American News Company]], which had a virtual [[monopoly]] on all comics except DC's. From 1952 to 1957 [[Atlas Comics (1950s)|Atlas Comics]] publisher [[Martin Goodman (publisher)|Martin Goodman]] distributed his company's comics to newsstands through his self-owned distributor, Atlas. He then switched to American News \u2014 which shortly afterward lost a [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] [[lawsuit]] and discontinued its business.<ref>Jones, Gerard. ''Men of Tomorrow: Geeks, Gangsters, and the Birth of the Comic Book'' (Basic Books, 2004).</ref> Atlas was left without distribution and was forced to turn to its biggest rival, [[DC Comics|National (DC) Comics]] which imposed draconian restrictions on Goodman's company. As then-Atlas editor [[Stan Lee]] recalled in a 1988 interview:\n{{quote|text=... [We had been] turning out 40, 50, 60 books a month, maybe more, and ... suddenly we went ... to either eight or 12 books a month, which was all Independent News Distributors would accept from us.<ref name=\"Stan and Roy\">{{cite news|url=http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/02stanroy.html |title=Stan the Man & Roy the Boy: A Conversation Between Stan Lee and Roy Thomas |work=[[Comic Book Artist]] |issue=2 |date=Summer 1998 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5lHwfKOI2?url=http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/02stanroy.html |archivedate=November 14, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\n[[American Comics Group]], another comic book publisher from the era (also with ties to Harry Donenfeld), was distributed by Independent News, as were such popular magazines as ''[[Playboy]]'' and ''[[Family Circle]]''.<ref name=\"Cooke\">Cooke, Jon B. \"Donenfeld's Comics: A Talk with Irwin Donenfeld, 1960s DC Editorial Director,\" Comic Book Artist Collection, vol. 2. (TwoMorrows Publishing, 2002), p. 67.</ref>\n\n[[Jack Liebowitz]] stayed with Independent News until 1965, eventually becoming a co-owner.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=LIEBOWITZ%2c+JACK Liebowitz entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref> [[Irwin Donenfeld]], who was DC's editorial director in the 1960s, was also a vice president of Independent News.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=DONENFELD%2c+IRWIN Donenfeld entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>\n\n=== Sale and demise ===\nIn 1967, National Periodical Publications (including Independent News) was purchased by [[Kinney National Company]], which later purchased [[Warner Bros.-Seven Arts]] and became [[Warner Communications]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/dc.htm \"DC Comics,\"] Don Markstein's Toonopedia.</ref> The Donenfelds and their \"crew\" were out, and new management came in. By 1970, Independent News was defunct, absorbed into a larger and changing distribution business. Independent News' last president was [[Harold Chamberlin]], who served from 1968-1970. Chamblerin went on to become president of Warner Publishing from 1970\u20131979.<ref>[http://www.bailsprojects.com/bio.aspx?Name=CHAMBERLIN%2c+HAROLD Chamberlin entry], Who's Who of American Comic Books, 1928\u20131999.</ref>  As [[List of assets owned by Time Warner|Warner Publishing Services]], the company was named by DC Comics as one of the honorees in the company's 50th anniversary publication ''[[Fifty Who Made DC Great]]''.<ref>{{Cite comic| writer = Marx, Barry| cowriters = [[Joey Cavalieri|Cavalieri, Joey]] and Hill, Thomas| artist = Petruccio, Steven | editor = Marx, Barry| story = Warner Publishing Services Fifty Years of Distributing Comics| title = Fifty Who Made DC Great| date = 1985| publisher = DC Comics| page = 12| panel = | id = }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[American News Company]]\n* [[Direct market]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Magazine publishing]]\n[[Category:Book distributors]]\n[[Category:Comics industry]]\n[[Category:DC Comics]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSale and demise:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1968-1970 \u2192 1968\u20131970", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_News"}
{"title_page": "Independent Network Charismatic Christianity", "text_new": "{{short description|Movement within evangelical charismatic Christianity}}\n'''Independent Network Charismatic (INC) Christianity''' is a movement within [[evangelical charismatic movement|evangelical charismatic Christianity]] which is focused on the authority of charismatic [[apostle]]s and seeks the wholesale transformation of society. The term was first used in 2017 by [[sociology|sociologists]] Brad Christerson and Richard Flory in their book ''The Rise of Network Christianity: How Independent Leaders are Changing the Religious Landscape'' to describe the rapid growth of a form of [[Protestantism|Protestant Christianity]] from 1970\u20132010, and has since been adopted by other commentators. The movement is distinguished from other forms of [[Christianity]] by its use of [[network governance]], based on networks of charismatic apostles, rather than more traditional church structures and hierarchies. These networks are sustained by the use of new communications technologies such as [[social media]], which both facilitates communication between leaders in the network and enables leaders to build a following which is not tied to a geographical area. It is characterised by belief in and encouragement of the use of the supernatural [[spiritual gifts|gifts of the Holy Spirit]], along with a focus on the transformation of society according to Christian values through [[prayer]] and by Christians reaching positions of leadership in the areas of business, government, media, arts and entertainment, education, family, and religion. INC Christianity tends to be [[conservatism|politically conservative]] and, in the US, associated with support for [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians.\n\nThe movement has its roots in the 1960s and 1970s [[Calvary Chapel]] and [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard]] movements, with INC Christianity emerging as leaders in these movements sought to break free from organisational structures and formed informal affinity networks. According to Christerson and Flory, INC is the fastest growing Christian group in the US. As a movement, it has been particularly appealing to younger people, especially [[millennials]].\n\n==Distinguishing features==\n[[File:Bill Johnson teaching.jpg|thumb|[[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]], senior leader of [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)|Bethel Church]]; both Johnson and the church have been described by various commentators as part of INC Christianity.]]\nIndependent Network Christianity is not a [[Religious denomination|denomination]] but rather a network of independent church and [[parachurch]] leaders. Whereas more traditional church movements (which, in this case, includes neo-Charismatic movements established in the 1970s such as Vineyard, Calvary Chapel, and [[Hope Chapel]]) have sought to build [[Church (congregation)|congregations]] and create franchises of affiliated churches, INC leaders prefer to try to directly influence the beliefs and practices of individuals, regardless of their personal and denominational affiliations. Individual [[Salvation in Christianity|salvation]] is regarded as more important than building church congregations; without any formal denomination or movement, individual leaders are connected by informal yet powerful co-operative networks.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, p. 8.</ref> INC can thus be described as operating a kind of [[network governance]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref>\n\nLeaders in the INC network are referred to by insiders as apostles. Apostles tend to be [[Charismatic authority|charismatic]] in the [[Max Weber|Weberian]] sense of being seen to possess a supernatural authority which authenticates their ministry. An international network of apostles is facilitated by modern communication technologies such as the [[internet]], allowing the sharing of ideas and pursuit of joint projects without the limitations of operating within a hierarchical structure.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 50\u201453.</ref> These modern technologies allow INC leaders to build international ministries and followings, using the internet and [[social media]] to create interconnected online venues which do not depend of geographical ties. Followers engage primarily with leaders through these online forums, sometimes travelling to attend conferences.<ref>Smith 2018.</ref><ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\nIn their book, Christerson & Flory cite [[Ch\u00e9 Ahn]] and his [[Harvest International Ministries]], [[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]] and [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)|Bethel Church]], and [[Mike Bickle (minister)|Mike Bickle]] and the [[International House of Prayer]] as examples of INC leaders and organisations.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, 32\u201442.</ref> Richard Ostling has also named [[Cindy Jacobs]] and [[Chuck Pierce]] as INC leaders.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n===Beliefs===\nExisting within charismatic Christianity, INC leaders and organisations believe in the continued operation of the supernatural [[spiritual gift]]s of the [[Holy Spirit]], such as [[faith healing#|supernatural healing]], [[miracles]], [[prophecy]] and [[glossolalia|speaking in tongues]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 2:33.</ref> Supernatural activity is not limited to charismatic leaders; schools such as [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)#Bethel School of Supernatural Ministry|Bethel School of Supernatural Ministry]] teach their students to practice supernatural gifts themselves and use them in the community. Christerson and Flory argue that the promise of direct experience of the supernatural is attractive to young people and a key draw for them becoming involved in INC organisations.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 84\u201486.</ref> Dyron B. Daughrity, a professor of religion and philosophy at [[Pepperdine University]], has noted that the charismatic beliefs and practices of International House of Prayer, an INC church, combined with the online accessibility of its content, has made it particularly appealing to [[millennials]].<ref>Daughrity 2018, pp. 65\u201466.</ref>\n\nAs well as belief in the supernatural gits of the Holy Spirit, a defining characteristic of INC Christianity is belief in social transformation. In contrast with classic [[pentecostalism]], which tends to hold out little hope for social justice in this world and thus focuses its efforts on [[evangelism]] and discipleship, many INC groups believe that heaven can be made on earth through the action of Christians.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, p. 92.</ref> This commitment to social change involves the desire to see INC Christians in positions of leadership in the \"seven mountains of culture\": business, government, media, arts and entertainment, education, family, and religion.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 2:51.</ref> The intention is to create a \"trickle down effect\", whereby the values of Christians who reach the top of these mountains will ultimately influence the whole of American and global society.<ref>Daughrity 2018, p. 66.</ref> INC Christianity tends to be politically [[conservatism|conservative]] and, in the [[United States]], supportive of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], with INC leaders regularly endorsing Republican candidates. In 2016, Mike Bickle endorsed [[Ted Cruz|Ted Cruz's]] bid for the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries|Republican presidential nomination]] and Lance Wallnau, another INC leader, supported [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidential bid. Philosopher [[James K. A. Smith]] has suggested that the religious mindset offered by INC Christianity \u2014 that of deference to powerful and charismatic leaders \u2014 could partly explain the growth of [[populism]] which led to the [[election of Donald Trump]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref> Journalist [[Richard Ostling]] has suggested that INC support of Trump, some of which regards him as an outsider anointed by God, in the mould of [[King Cyrus]], deserves greater press scrutiny.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n==History==\nChristerson and Flory identify the roots of Independent Network Charismatic Christianity in the [[Calvary Chapel]] and [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard]] movements of the late 1960s and 1970s, and [[John Wimber]] as the individual with whom many of the early INC leaders had a connection. Controversies within the Vineyard in the late 1980s and early 1990s \u2014 specifically the Vineyard's association with the [[Kansas City Prophets]] and the [[Toronto Blessing]] \u2014 culminated in some leading figures within the early Vineyard leaving the movement and, rather than establishing their own churches or denominations, these leaders formed a looser network which enabled individual leaders to build their own ministries without the limitations or responsibilities involved in managing groups of churches. These leaders, including [[C. Peter Wagner]], [[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]], [[Ch\u00e9 Ahn]] and [[Mike Bickle (minister)|Mike Bickle]], focused their efforts on spreading their personal influence through these networks and the use of new media technologies.<ref>Christerson & Flory, pp. 18\u201426.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to research by Christerson and Flory, \"INC Christianity is the fastest-growing Christian group in America and possibly around the world.\" While overall Protestant church attendance shrunk by 0.05% on average per year between 1970 and 2010, \"independent neo-charismatic congregations\", of which INC congregations are a subset, grew by an average of 3.24% per year in the same timeframe.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 3\u20144.</ref><ref>Christerson & Flory 2017b.</ref> INC Christianity has been particularly effective at attracting young people, especially millennials.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017b.</ref><ref>Daughrity 2018, p. 66.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 21:34.</ref> Ostling has suggested that this appeal is the result of INC's more flexible model of Christian belonging which prioritises experience over theology, as well as its effective use of social media.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite episode | title =Bringing Heaven to Earth | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p055c9bc | series =Heart and Soul  | network =BBC | station =[[BBC World Service|World Service]] | air-date =18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Daughrity |first1=Dyron B.  |date=2018 |title=Rising: The Amazing Story of Christianity's Resurrection in the Global South |location=Minneapolis |publisher=Fortress Press}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Christerson |first1=Brad |last2=Flory |first2=Richard |date=2017a |title=The Rise of Network Christianity: How Independent Leaders are Changing the Religious Landscape |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://theconversation.com/how-a-christian-movement-is-growing-rapidly-in-the-midst-of-religious-decline-73507 |title=How a Christian movement is growing rapidly in the midst of religious decline |last1=Christerson |first1=Brad |last2=Flory |first2=Richard |date=2017b |website=The Conversation |access-date=28 November 2019}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2017/10/18/is-this-the-fastest-growing-christian-group-in-america-and-perhaps-the-world |title=Is this the 'fastest-growing Christian group in America,' and perhaps the world? |last=Ostling |first=Richard |author-link=Richard and Joan Ostling |date=2017 |website=Get Religion |access-date=17 November 2019}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/how-to-find-god-on-youtube/ |title=How to Find God (on YouTube) |last=Smith |first=James K. A. |author-link=James K. A. Smith |date=2018 |website=Los Angeles Review of Books |access-date=17 November 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Charismatic and Pentecostal Christianity]]\n[[Category:Protestantism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Movement within evangelical charismatic Christianity}}\n'''Independent Network Charismatic (INC) Christianity''' is a movement within [[evangelical charismatic movement|evangelical charismatic Christianity]] which is focused on the authority of charismatic [[apostle]]s and seeks the wholesale transformation of society. The term was first used in 2017 by [[sociology|sociologists]] Brad Christerson and Richard Flory in their book ''The Rise of Network Christianity: How Independent Leaders are Changing the Religious Landscape'' to describe the rapid growth of a form of [[Protestantism|Protestant Christianity]] from 1970\u20142010, and has since been adopted by other commentators. The movement is distinguished from other forms of [[Christianity]] by its use of [[network governance]], based on networks of charismatic apostles, rather than more traditional church structures and hierarchies. These networks are sustained by the use of new communications technologies such as [[social media]], which both facilitates communication between leaders in the network and enables leaders to build a following which is not tied to a geographical area. It is characterised by belief in and encouragement of the use of the supernatural [[spiritual gifts|gifts of the Holy Spirit]], along with a focus on the transformation of society according to Christian values through [[prayer]] and by Christians reaching positions of leadership in the areas of business, government, media, arts and entertainment, education, family, and religion. INC Christianity tends to be [[conservatism|politically conservative]] and, in the US, associated with support for [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians.\n\nThe movement has its roots in the 1960s and 1970s [[Calvary Chapel]] and [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard]] movements, with INC Christianity emerging as leaders in these movements sought to break free from organisational structures and formed informal affinity networks. According to Christerson and Flory, INC is the fastest growing Christian group in the US. As a movement, it has been particularly appealing to younger people, especially [[millennials]].\n\n==Distinguishing features==\n[[File:Bill Johnson teaching.jpg|thumb|[[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]], senior leader of [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)|Bethel Church]]; both Johnson and the church have been described by various commentators as part of INC Christianity.]]\nIndependent Network Christianity is not a [[Religious denomination|denomination]] but rather a network of independent church and [[parachurch]] leaders. Whereas more traditional church movements (which, in this case, includes neo-Charismatic movements established in the 1970s such as Vineyard, Calvary Chapel, and [[Hope Chapel]]) have sought to build [[Church (congregation)|congregations]] and create franchises of affiliated churches, INC leaders prefer to try to directly influence the beliefs and practices of individuals, regardless of their personal and denominational affiliations. Individual [[Salvation in Christianity|salvation]] is regarded as more important than building church congregations; without any formal denomination or movement, individual leaders are connected by informal yet powerful co-operative networks.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, p. 8.</ref> INC can thus be described as operating a kind of [[network governance]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref>\n\nLeaders in the INC network are referred to by insiders as apostles. Apostles tend to be [[Charismatic authority|charismatic]] in the [[Max Weber|Weberian]] sense of being seen to possess a supernatural authority which authenticates their ministry. An international network of apostles is facilitated by modern communication technologies such as the [[internet]], allowing the sharing of ideas and pursuit of joint projects without the limitations of operating within a hierarchical structure.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 50\u201453.</ref> These modern technologies allow INC leaders to build international ministries and followings, using the internet and [[social media]] to create interconnected online venues which do not depend of geographical ties. Followers engage primarily with leaders through these online forums, sometimes travelling to attend conferences.<ref>Smith 2018.</ref><ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\nIn their book, Christerson & Flory cite [[Ch\u00e9 Ahn]] and his [[Harvest International Ministries]], [[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]] and [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)|Bethel Church]], and [[Mike Bickle (minister)|Mike Bickle]] and the [[International House of Prayer]] as examples of INC leaders and organisations.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, 32\u201442.</ref> Richard Ostling has also named [[Cindy Jacobs]] and [[Chuck Pierce]] as INC leaders.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n===Beliefs===\nExisting within charismatic Christianity, INC leaders and organisations believe in the continued operation of the supernatural [[spiritual gift]]s of the [[Holy Spirit]], such as [[faith healing#|supernatural healing]], [[miracles]], [[prophecy]] and [[glossolalia|speaking in tongues]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 2:33.</ref> Supernatural activity is not limited to charismatic leaders; schools such as [[Bethel Church (Redding, California)#Bethel School of Supernatural Ministry|Bethel School of Supernatural Ministry]] teach their students to practice supernatural gifts themselves and use them in the community. Christerson and Flory argue that the promise of direct experience of the supernatural is attractive to young people and a key draw for them becoming involved in INC organisations.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 84\u201486.</ref> Dyron B. Daughrity, a professor of religion and philosophy at [[Pepperdine University]], has noted that the charismatic beliefs and practices of International House of Prayer, an INC church, combined with the online accessibility of its content, has made it particularly appealing to [[millennials]].<ref>Daughrity 2018, pp. 65\u201466.</ref>\n\nAs well as belief in the supernatural gits of the Holy Spirit, a defining characteristic of INC Christianity is belief in social transformation. In contrast with classic [[pentecostalism]], which tends to hold out little hope for social justice in this world and thus focuses its efforts on [[evangelism]] and discipleship, many INC groups believe that heaven can be made on earth through the action of Christians.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, p. 92.</ref> This commitment to social change involves the desire to see INC Christians in positions of leadership in the \"seven mountains of culture\": business, government, media, arts and entertainment, education, family, and religion.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 2:51.</ref> The intention is to create a \"trickle down effect\", whereby the values of Christians who reach the top of these mountains will ultimately influence the whole of American and global society.<ref>Daughrity 2018, p. 66.</ref> INC Christianity tends to be politically [[conservatism|conservative]] and, in the [[United States]], supportive of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], with INC leaders regularly endorsing Republican candidates. In 2016, Mike Bickle endorsed [[Ted Cruz|Ted Cruz's]] bid for the [[2016 Republican Party presidential primaries|Republican presidential nomination]] and Lance Wallnau, another INC leader, supported [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidential bid. Philosopher [[James K. A. Smith]] has suggested that the religious mindset offered by INC Christianity \u2014 that of deference to powerful and charismatic leaders \u2014 could partly explain the growth of [[populism]] which led to the [[election of Donald Trump]].<ref>Smith 2018.</ref> Journalist [[Richard Ostling]] has suggested that INC support of Trump, some of which regards him as an outsider anointed by God, in the mould of [[King Cyrus]], deserves greater press scrutiny.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n==History==\nChristerson and Flory identify the roots of Independent Network Charismatic Christianity in the [[Calvary Chapel]] and [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard]] movements of the late 1960s and 1970s, and [[John Wimber]] as the individual with whom many of the early INC leaders had a connection. Controversies within the Vineyard in the late 1980s and early 1990s \u2014 specifically the Vineyard's association with the [[Kansas City Prophets]] and the [[Toronto Blessing]] \u2014 culminated in some leading figures within the early Vineyard leaving the movement and, rather than establishing their own churches or denominations, these leaders formed a looser network which enabled individual leaders to build their own ministries without the limitations or responsibilities involved in managing groups of churches. These leaders, including [[C. Peter Wagner]], [[Bill Johnson (pastor)|Bill Johnson]], [[Ch\u00e9 Ahn]] and [[Mike Bickle (minister)|Mike Bickle]], focused their efforts on spreading their personal influence through these networks and the use of new media technologies.<ref>Christerson & Flory, pp. 18\u201426.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to research by Christerson and Flory, \"INC Christianity is the fastest-growing Christian group in America and possibly around the world.\" While overall Protestant church attendance shrunk by 0.05% on average per year between 1970 and 2010, \"independent neo-charismatic congregations\", of which INC congregations are a subset, grew by an average of 3.24% per year in the same timeframe.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017a, pp. 3\u20144.</ref><ref>Christerson & Flory 2017b.</ref> INC Christianity has been particularly effective at attracting young people, especially millennials.<ref>Christerson & Flory 2017b.</ref><ref>Daughrity 2018, p. 66.</ref><ref>''Bringing Heaven to Earth'', 21:34.</ref> Ostling has suggested that this appeal is the result of INC's more flexible model of Christian belonging which prioritises experience over theology, as well as its effective use of social media.<ref>Ostling 2017.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite episode | title =Bringing Heaven to Earth | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p055c9bc | series =Heart and Soul  | network =BBC | station =[[BBC World Service|World Service]] | air-date =18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Daughrity |first1=Dyron B.  |date=2018 |title=Rising: The Amazing Story of Christianity's Resurrection in the Global South |location=Minneapolis |publisher=Fortress Press}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Christerson |first1=Brad |last2=Flory |first2=Richard |date=2017a |title=The Rise of Network Christianity: How Independent Leaders are Changing the Religious Landscape |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://theconversation.com/how-a-christian-movement-is-growing-rapidly-in-the-midst-of-religious-decline-73507 |title=How a Christian movement is growing rapidly in the midst of religious decline |last1=Christerson |first1=Brad |last2=Flory |first2=Richard |date=2017b |website=The Conversation |access-date=28 November 2019}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.getreligion.org/getreligion/2017/10/18/is-this-the-fastest-growing-christian-group-in-america-and-perhaps-the-world |title=Is this the 'fastest-growing Christian group in America,' and perhaps the world? |last=Ostling |first=Richard |author-link=Richard and Joan Ostling |date=2017 |website=Get Religion |access-date=17 November 2019}}\n*{{cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/how-to-find-god-on-youtube/ |title=How to Find God (on YouTube) |last=Smith |first=James K. A. |author-link=James K. A. Smith |date=2018 |website=Los Angeles Review of Books |access-date=17 November 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Charismatic and Pentecostal Christianity]]\n[[Category:Protestantism]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1970\u20142010 \u2192 1970\u20132010", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_Network_Charismatic_Christianity"}
{"title_page": "National Republican Party (Costa Rica)", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name          = National Republican Party\n| native_name   = Partido Republicano Nacional\n| colorcode     = {{National Republican Party (Costa Rica)/meta/color}}\n| leader1_title = Leaders\n| leader1_name  = [[Ricardo Jim\u00e9nez Oreamuno]]<br/>[[Le\u00f3n Cort\u00e9s Castro]]<br/>[[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia|Rafael Calder\u00f3n]]<br/>[[Teodoro Picado Michalski]]\n| foundation    = {{start date|1901}}\n| dissolution   = {{end date|1952}}\n| successor     = [[National Unification Party (Costa Rica)|National Unification Party]]<br/>{{small|(Not legal successor)}}\n| ideology      = [[Christian democracy]]<br/>[[Social liberalism]]\n| position      = [[Centre-right]]\n| colors        = {{color box|border=darkgray|#0000FF}} [[Blue]] {{color box|border=darkgray|#FFFF00}} [[Yellow]] {{color box|border=darkgray|#FF0000}} [[Red]]\n| flag          = PRN-flag.PNG\n| country       = Costa Rica\n}}\n\nThe '''National Republican Party''' ({{lang-es|Partido Republicano Nacional}}; PRN) was a political party in [[Costa Rica]]. \n\n==History==\nA loosely [[Liberalism|liberal]] party was founded under the leadership of [[M\u00e1ximo Fern\u00e1ndez Alvarado]] known simply as Republican Party in 1901, its candidate was Fern\u00e1ndez himself three times. The party's candidate [[Ricardo Jim\u00e9nez Oreamuno]] was elected president in 1910. A non-elected president member of the party was [[Alfredo Gonz\u00e1lez Flores]] who became the only [[president of Costa Rica]] appointed by the [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Congress]].<ref name=OSO>{{cite book|last=Booth|first=John A.|title=Political Parties in Costa Rica: Democratic Stability and Party System Change in a Latin American Context|date=January 2008|publisher=Oxford Scholarship Online|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199289653|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199289653.001.0001/acprof-9780199289653-chapter-11|edition=1|author2=yes |editor=Paul Webb and Stephen White|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter electing Jim\u00e9nez in three different occasions, the party also successfully nominated [[Le\u00f3n Cort\u00e9s Castro]] in 1936, [[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia]] in 1940 and [[Teodoro Picado Michalski]] in 1944 becoming a [[Dominant-party system|dominant party]]. During Calder\u00f3n's leadership the party moved toward [[Christian democracy]] and [[Christian socialism]] making some of the country's first [[social reform]]s in alliance with the [[People's Vanguard Party (Costa Rica)|Communist Party]]. Criticism over [[corruption]], [[authoritarianism]] and [[voting fraud]] against the party and the results of the 1948 election in which the republican-dominated Congress overturned the elections because its candidate Calder\u00f3n apparently lost cause the [[Costa Rican Civil War|1948 Civil War]].<ref name=OSO/> After that the party will be banned for a while and its leaders Calder\u00f3n and Picado in exile. The party would have still relevance in the political system once democracy was restored but only would attain power in coalition with liberal forces (the party endorsed the successful candidacies of [[Mario Echandi]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Trejos Fern\u00e1ndez|Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Trejos]] as part of alliances with other parties), eventually disappearing.<ref name=OSO/>\n\n[[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Fournier]] (Calder\u00f3n's son) founded a new party named [[Social Christian Republican Party]] in 2014 using the traditional party's colors and flag.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Costa Rican political parties}}\n[[Category:Christian democratic parties in North America]]\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in Costa Rica]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name          = National Republican Party\n| native_name   = Partido Republicano Nacional\n| colorcode     = {{National Republican Party (Costa Rica)/meta/color}}\n| leader1_title = Leaders\n| leader1_name  = [[Ricardo Jim\u00e9nez Oreamuno]]<br/>[[Le\u00f3n Cort\u00e9s Castro]]<br/>[[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia|Rafael Calder\u00f3n]]<br/>[[Teodoro Picado Michalski]]\n| foundation    = {{start date|1901}}\n| dissolution   = {{end date|1952}}\n| successor     = [[National Unification Party (Costa Rica)|National Unification Party]]<br/>{{small|(Not legal successor)}}\n| ideology      = [[Christian democracy]]<br/>[[Social liberalism]]\n| position      = [[Centre-right]]\n| colors        = {{color box|border=darkgray|#0000FF}} [[Blue]] {{color box|border=darkgray|#FFFF00}} [[Yellow]] {{color box|border=darkgray|#FF0000}} [[Red]]\n| flag          = PRN-flag.PNG\n| country       = Costa Rica\n}}\n\nThe '''National Republican Party''' ({{lang-es|Partido Republicano Nacional}}; PRN) was a political party in [[Costa Rica]]. \n\n==History==\nA loosely [[Liberalism|liberal]] party was founded under the leadership of [[M\u00e1ximo Fern\u00e1ndez Alvarado]] known simply as Republican Party in 1901, its candidate was Fern\u00e1ndez himself three times. The party\u2019s candidate [[Ricardo Jim\u00e9nez Oreamuno]] was elected president in 1910. A non-elected president member of the party was [[Alfredo Gonz\u00e1lez Flores]] who became the only [[president of Costa Rica]] appointed by the [[Legislative Assembly of Costa Rica|Congress]].<ref name=OSO>{{cite book|last=Booth|first=John A.|title=Political Parties in Costa Rica: Democratic Stability and Party System Change in a Latin American Context|date=January 2008|publisher=Oxford Scholarship Online|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199289653|url=http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199289653.001.0001/acprof-9780199289653-chapter-11|edition=1|author2=yes |editor=Paul Webb and Stephen White|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter electing Jim\u00e9nez in three different occasions, the party also successfully nominated [[Le\u00f3n Cort\u00e9s Castro]] in 1936, [[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Guardia]] in 1940 and [[Teodoro Picado Michalski]] in 1944 becoming a [[Dominant-party system|dominant party]]. During Calder\u00f3n's leadership the party moved toward [[Christian democracy]] and [[Christian socialism]] making some of the country's first [[social reform]]s in alliance with the [[People's Vanguard Party (Costa Rica)|Communist Party]]. Criticism over [[corruption]], [[authoritarianism]] and [[voting fraud]] against the party and the results of the 1948 election in which the republican-dominated Congress overturned the elections because its candidate Calder\u00f3n apparently lost cause the [[Costa Rican Civil War|1948 Civil War]].<ref name=OSO/> After that the party will be banned for a while and its leaders Calder\u00f3n and Picado in exile. The party would have still relevance in the political system once democracy was restored but only would attain power in coalition with liberal forces (the party endorsed the successful candidacies of [[Mario Echandi]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Trejos Fern\u00e1ndez|Jos\u00e9 Joaqu\u00edn Trejos]] as part of alliances with other parties), eventually disappearing.<ref name=OSO/>\n\n[[Rafael \u00c1ngel Calder\u00f3n Fournier]] (Calder\u00f3n\u2019s son) founded a new party named [[Social Christian Republican Party]] in 2014 using the traditional party\u2019s colors and flag.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Costa Rican political parties}}\n[[Category:Christian democratic parties in North America]]\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in Costa Rica]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Republican_Party_(Costa_Rica)"}
{"title_page": "Sonia Falcone", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n{{artist-stub}} \n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = Sonia Falcone\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name   = Sonia Montero\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1965|03|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]], Bolivia\n| nationality = Bolivian\n| field       = Painting and Installation\n}}\n\n'''Sonia Falcone''', born March 27, 1965 in [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]], [[Bolivia]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artealdia.com/Reviews|title=Reviews - Arte Al D\u00eda|website=www.artealdia.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> is a Bolivian artist known for her painting and installation work.\n\n== Early life ==\nAt an early age Falcone moved to the [[United States]] where she began to paint. As a child, she wanted to be a dentist; she attended nursing school but finally chose art as her career. Sonia represented her homeland in Japan with the title of [[Miss Bolivia]] International 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eju.tv/2013/07/sonia-montero-maestra-del-estilo/|title=Sonia Montero, maestra del estilo|website=eju.tv|language=es|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />  She is an activist for health and education, a supporter and promoter of children's rights, and protector of women who suffered domestic violence.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n== Philanthropic work ==\n\nFalcone was invited as a volunteer by the [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]] Center for the Arts Museum ([[Arizona]], [[United States]]) and devoted her time to community projects related to and in support of art: improvement and maintenance of the opera, theatre, and the Museum of the city. As a member of the Board, she promoted the involvement of marginalized Latino communities to arts-related tasks. She is the founder of [[Essant\u00e9 Corporation]], a multinational entity established specifically for people seeking better health and greater opportunities in their lives.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=citation required}} She is also the founder and president of the AMA Saving the Oceans Foundation<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://tendenciaelartedeviajar.com/en/2019/11/on-tendencia-en/ama-foundation-in-the-fight-to-save-the-oceans/|title=AMA foundation in the endeavor to save the oceans|date=2019-11-12|website=Tendencia Magazine - travel, hotels, restaurants in Los Cabos|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.diarioelindependiente.mx/2020/03/museo-de-la-ballena-podria-tener-como-nueva-sede-los-cabos|title=Museo de la Ballena...|last=Yanez|first=Brenda|date=2020-04-13|website=Diario El Independiente|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>, as well as the Sonia Falcone Foundation.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.com.mx/noticia/851033/0/la-escultora-sonia-falcone-y-su-arte-sostenible/|title=La escultora Sonia Falcone y su arte sostenible|date=2020-01-02|website=www.20minutos.com.mx - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es-MX|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n== Artistic career ==\nFalcone was invited as a volunteer by the [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]] Center for the Arts Museum ([[Arizona]], [[United States]]) and devoted her time to community projects related to and in support of art: improvement and maintenance of the opera, theatre, and the Museum of the city. As a member of the Board, she promoted the involvement of marginalized Latino communities to arts-related tasks. She is the founder of [[Essant\u00e9 Corporation]], a multinational entity established specifically for people seeking better health and greater opportunities in their lives.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=citation required}} She is also the founder and president of the AMA Saving the Oceans Foundation.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://tendenciaelartedeviajar.com/en/2019/11/on-tendencia-en/ama-foundation-in-the-fight-to-save-the-oceans/|title=AMA foundation in the endeavor to save the oceans|date=2019-11-12|website=Tendencia Magazine - travel, hotels, restaurants in Los Cabos|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diarioelindependiente.mx/2020/03/museo-de-la-ballena-podria-tener-como-nueva-sede-los-cabos|title=Museo de la Ballena...|last=Yanez|first=Brenda|date=2020-04-13|website=Diario El Independiente|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\nFalcone exhibited her work in [[La Paz]] (Nota Gallery) in July 2010{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=citation required}} and [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra|Santa Cruz]] (Lorca Gallery) in September 2010{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=citation required}} - [[Bolivia]], in PINTA [[New York City]] (December 2010), [[Miami International Art Fair]] <ref>[http://mia-artfair.com/press_articles/releases/print/mia_release_features.pdf Press Article in mia-artfair.com ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821212926/http://mia-artfair.com/press_articles/releases/print/mia_release_features.pdf |date=2011-08-21 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/best-art-from-miami-international-art-fair-6489236|title=Best Art From Miami International Art Fair|last=McCorquodale|first=Amanda|date=2011-01-14|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> (January 2011) and from June 6, in PINTA <ref>[http://www.undo.net/it/mostra/121216 Article in www.undu.net]</ref>[[London]] (June 2011).\n\nIn these exhibitions, Falcone manifests another phase of her personality with her most well-known work \"Windows of the Soul\", revealing elements that reflect her life experience. Spirituality is a central element in her work. Her spiritual ideal can be found in all structures, cosmic or individual, organic or inorganic, but achieves its full expression in the human form, shown in her monumental multicolored pieces, with rainbows, snow-capped peaks of the Andes, shadows that banish sunrises, the construction of a world with llamas and fish and where, living the art of war, the sun of justice rose and the drops of blood became art and poetry.\n\nVideo Art Installation, a major piece of this artist, participated in the XVII Bienal de Arte de [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]], where Sonia was invited to participate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.my-bolivia.com/best-video-installation-art-at-the-biennale-in-santa-cruz-bolivia-by-sonia-falcone/|title=Best Video Installation Art at the Biennale in Santa Cruz Bolivia by SONIA FALCONE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.my-bolivia.com/best-video-installation-art-at-the-biennale-in-santa-cruz-bolivia-by-sonia-falcone/|title=Best Video Installation Art at the Biennale in Santa Cruz Bolivia by SONIA FALCONE|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the [[3rd millennium|third millennium]], after receiving an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorate]] from Trinity College of Graduate Studies <ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Businesswoman-Philanthropist+Sonia+Falcone+to+Receive+Honorary...-a075602619 PR Newswire June 18 2001]</ref> in \"Spirituality and Psychology\", she joined her social and artistic work, viewing art as a tool that could be used not only to understand people's problems, but also to help them think.\n\n\"Passions of the Soul\", one of her most recent works, achieves a rapport between art and game, trying to reach the adult and the child within by creating metaphors that express a philosophy of life.\n\nFalcone's work has appeared in several collectives, mainly in [[Phoenix City Government Convention Center]]\u2013 Civic Plaza, invited by the [[National Hispanic Woman Corporation]].  She has had solo exhibitions at the Museum of Phoenix, [[Calvin Charles Gallery]] in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]],{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=citation required}} and \"The Gallery\" in [[Cabo San Lucas]], [[Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oceanblueworld.com/make-it-happen/honoring-the-seas-with-sonia-falcones-ocean-scapes-baja-series-exhibition/|title=Honoring the Seas with Sonia Falcone's Ocean Scapes, Baja Series Exhibition|date=2020-03-05|website=Ocean Blue WORLD|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Falcone's colorful installation using spices and called ''Campo de Color'' was part of the Latin American Pavilion at the 2013 [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2013/may/29/venice-biennale-ai-weiwei-best-pictures|title=Venice Biennale: Ai Weiwei, Milla Jovovich and the best of the rest - in pictures|date=2013-05-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2017, that same installation work was included in the [[Nevada Museum of Art]] in Reno, NV group show titled \"Unsettled\", which also travelled to the [[Anchorage Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adn.com/arts/2018/05/10/anchorage-museums-unsettled-is-a-sensory-exploration-of-the-ever-changing-greater-west/|title=Anchorage Museum\u2019s \u2018Unsettled\u2019 is a sensory exploration of the ever-changing \u2018Greater West\u2019|date=2018-05-11|website=Anchorage Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> in Alaska, and California's [[Palm Springs Art Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2017/oct/31/art-exhibit-explores-exploitation-beauty-of-greate/|title=Art exhibit explores exploitation, beauty of 'Greater West' - Las Vegas Sun Newspaper|last=Sonner|first=Scott|last2=Press|first2=Associated|date=2017-10-31|website=lasvegassun.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nevadaart.org/art/exhibitions/unsettled/|title=Unsettled|website=Nevada Museum of Art|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palmspringslife.com/art-exhibitions-palm-springs/|title=Art Exhibitions Offer Large-Scale Perspective of the Desert|date=2018-12-10|website=Palm Springs Life|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Private life ==\nSonia Falcone (nee Montero) is married to businessman [[Pierre Falcone]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/blog/17040|title=Sonia Falcone's Opening Causes a Sensation in Monaco - Eric Deville - Digital Journal|website=www.digitaljournal.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and they have three children: Perrine, Eugenie and Pierre Philippe.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://artjed.com/artists/sonia-falcone/|title=Sonia Falcone : Art JED Gallery|website=artjed.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n* ''Passions of the Soul'' (2010)\n* ''Creation'' (2010)\n* ''Llama'' (2010)\n* ''Video art Installation'' (2010)\n* ''Drops of Blood Installation'' (2010)\n* ''Live Soul Installation'' (2010)\n* ''Blue Water'' (2008)\n* ''Dawn'' (2008)\n* ''Sun of Righteousness'' (2008)\n* ''All eyes on you'' (2011) Mixed media installation \u2013 160x60 cm\n* ''Walking on Eggshells'' (2011) Mixed media installation \u2013 200 aluminum cubes and 300 stainless steel eggs  - Dimensions variable\n* ''Self-portrait I, II, III'' (2011) 3D scanning printed on translucent photographic paper \u2013 76x121 cm\n* ''See no evil, Hear no evil, Speak no evil'' (2011) 3D scanning printed on translucent photographic paper \u2013 76x121 cm\n* ''Vertigo'' (2011)Oil on linen \u2013 180x108 cm\n* ''Vertigo'' (2011) 200x120 cm \u2013 Oil on linen\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{External links|section|date=September 2016}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.eldiario.net/noticias/2010/2010_11/nt101102/6_01clt.php |title=Sonia Falcone presents her work Windows of the Soul |author= |date=2010-10-02 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=8 June 2011}}\n* [http://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/best-art-from-miami-international-art-fair-6489236 \"Best Art from Miami International Art Fair\" 2011-01-14]\n* {{cite web |